1
00:00:29,242 --> 00:00:30,436
[Phone rings]

2
00:00:31,144 --> 00:00:32,270
MAN:
<i>Hello?</i>

3
00:00:32,379 --> 00:00:34,210
<i>Hey, what's up?</i>

4
00:00:35,082 --> 00:00:38,518
<i>What are you talking about?</i>
<i>Reservations for what?</i>

5
00:00:39,720 --> 00:00:41,654
<i>Crystal, we're not even</i>
<i>seeing each other.</i>

6
00:00:41,755 --> 00:00:45,007
<i>We get together like</i>
<i>a couple of animals.</i>

7
00:00:48,161 --> 00:00:49,560
<i>No, I can't come over.</i>

8
00:00:49,663 --> 00:00:52,757
<i>I'm in the middle</i>
<i>of a business meeting.</i>

9
00:00:52,866 --> 00:00:54,356
[Angrily]
<i>Talk about what?</i>

10
00:00:54,468 --> 00:00:56,026
<i>Let's end it.</i>
<i>It's over.</i>

11
00:00:56,203 --> 00:00:58,637
<i>You don't exist.</i>
<i>I don't exist.</i>

12
00:00:58,739 --> 00:01:01,708
<i>We don't exist.</i>

13
00:01:02,309 --> 00:01:03,435
[Shuts phone]

14
00:01:03,543 --> 00:01:04,339
Poof!

15
00:01:04,444 --> 00:01:06,071
[Laughter]

16
00:01:48,255 --> 00:01:51,315
Any other substances,
Mr. Gaines?

17
00:01:52,626 --> 00:01:53,490
Needles?

18
00:01:55,095 --> 00:01:57,222
Fooled around a little bit
when I was a kid.

19
00:01:57,397 --> 00:01:58,830
[Sighs]

20
00:01:58,932 --> 00:02:02,390
You have hepatitis C,
Mr. Gaines.

21
00:02:02,569 --> 00:02:04,594
It is progressive and late.

22
00:02:04,771 --> 00:02:06,898
Your liver shows signs
of advanced degeneration.

23
00:02:07,073 --> 00:02:10,201
Kidney function is diminished,
as well as your immune system,

24
00:02:10,310 --> 00:02:13,507
and your white count is very high.

25
00:02:17,584 --> 00:02:22,612
These will help the symptoms
and slow down the process.

26
00:02:24,858 --> 00:02:26,849
I strongly suggest
you talk to your family

27
00:02:26,960 --> 00:02:29,360
about a partial liver transplant.

28
00:02:29,463 --> 00:02:32,523
You're in no condition
to wait on a long list,

29
00:02:32,632 --> 00:02:34,327
not even a good candidate.

30
00:02:34,434 --> 00:02:38,063
A blood relative is your best bet.

31
00:02:38,171 --> 00:02:40,571
Do you have any grown children?

32
00:03:24,784 --> 00:03:26,649
Do I know you?

33
00:03:26,753 --> 00:03:30,280
I mean, I guess you got that flyer
from somewhere.

34
00:03:30,390 --> 00:03:31,254
A friend.

35
00:03:31,424 --> 00:03:32,448
Really.

36
00:03:32,559 --> 00:03:34,527
Which friend?

37
00:03:34,694 --> 00:03:35,854
[Grunts]

38
00:03:38,198 --> 00:03:40,496
Yes!

39
00:03:44,037 --> 00:03:45,334
I bet he can't even ride it.

40
00:03:46,473 --> 00:03:47,838
[Girl laughs]

41
00:03:47,941 --> 00:03:49,806
GUY:
Sucks for you, dude!

42
00:03:50,777 --> 00:03:53,712
[Engine turns over]

43
00:03:53,813 --> 00:03:54,837
[Laughter]

44
00:03:54,948 --> 00:03:56,006
BYSTANDER:
Loser!

45
00:03:58,218 --> 00:04:00,743
Dude, you are pathetic.

46
00:04:01,288 --> 00:04:02,721
<i>Adiós,</i> bro'!

47
00:04:42,929 --> 00:04:44,954
[Burglar alarm sounds]

48
00:05:35,982 --> 00:05:37,540
[Alarm rings]

49
00:05:43,623 --> 00:05:45,818
[Ringing stops]

50
00:05:47,861 --> 00:05:49,590
[Telephone rings]

51
00:05:52,432 --> 00:05:54,457
[Telephone rings]

52
00:05:57,804 --> 00:05:59,965
ANSWERING MACHINE: <i>You've</i>
<i>reached Carrie and Danny Gaines.</i>

53
00:06:00,073 --> 00:06:01,836
<i>Leave a message.</i>

54
00:06:01,941 --> 00:06:04,068
[Beep]

55
00:06:05,445 --> 00:06:06,810
[Disconnects phone]

56
00:06:07,981 --> 00:06:09,778
- CARRIE: I did it.
- MONA: What?

57
00:06:09,949 --> 00:06:12,144
I applied for that
San Francisco rotation.

58
00:06:12,252 --> 00:06:13,879
- Oh, I don't believe it.
- Mm-hmm.

59
00:06:13,987 --> 00:06:15,648
I probably wouldn't go, anyway.

60
00:06:15,755 --> 00:06:18,519
You've done so much for that kid.
He's not even yours!

61
00:06:18,625 --> 00:06:20,149
Mona.

62
00:06:20,326 --> 00:06:21,258
You know what I mean.

63
00:06:21,361 --> 00:06:23,454
I don't know what to do.
He aced out of school.

64
00:06:23,563 --> 00:06:27,260
He's got no interest
in anybody or anything.

65
00:06:27,367 --> 00:06:28,800
I shouldn't have even applied.

66
00:06:28,902 --> 00:06:32,065
The boy needs a male figure,
and so do you.

67
00:06:32,172 --> 00:06:34,697
Speaking of which...

68
00:06:34,874 --> 00:06:36,171
Take this.

69
00:06:38,244 --> 00:06:39,871
VINCE:
Hey.

70
00:06:39,979 --> 00:06:40,707
Hey.

71
00:06:41,314 --> 00:06:44,841
Can I, uh, interest you girls
in a cup of coffee?

72
00:06:45,585 --> 00:06:46,916
Uh, no thanks, Doctor.

73
00:06:47,087 --> 00:06:49,214
Oh, please, call me Vince.

74
00:06:50,924 --> 00:06:52,152
[Ambulance siren sounds]

75
00:06:52,258 --> 00:06:54,522
Well, maybe another time.

76
00:06:55,695 --> 00:06:57,060
Sure.

77
00:06:59,566 --> 00:07:01,761
- Well?
- What?

78
00:07:01,868 --> 00:07:03,267
Yeah, he's interested in me...

79
00:07:03,436 --> 00:07:06,200
a twice-divorced nurse pushing 40
raising a problem teenager.

80
00:07:06,306 --> 00:07:06,829
Mm-hmm.

81
00:07:07,006 --> 00:07:08,098
The guy lost a bet.

82
00:07:08,208 --> 00:07:11,439
Uh-huh, now,
I hear he's divorced.

83
00:07:11,544 --> 00:07:14,308
- I gotta go.
- Oh!

84
00:07:14,414 --> 00:07:15,938
- Oh, call me.
- Yeah, uh-huh.

85
00:07:16,049 --> 00:07:17,641
- We'll go shopping.
- Okay.

86
00:07:17,817 --> 00:07:19,808
- I'll see ya.
- Bye.

87
00:07:32,565 --> 00:07:35,500
Hey, you buy, you buy?

88
00:07:39,939 --> 00:07:41,839
Relax!

89
00:07:42,575 --> 00:07:46,033
[Police dispatch calls]

90
00:07:48,748 --> 00:07:50,477
INVESTIGATOR:
How long was he at the party?

91
00:07:50,583 --> 00:07:52,175
GIRL:
[Laughs]

92
00:07:52,285 --> 00:07:54,480
I don't know. I kicked him out.

93
00:07:54,654 --> 00:07:55,746
Well, maybe you've seen him before?

94
00:07:55,855 --> 00:07:57,482
Sometimes, around my high school.

95
00:07:57,590 --> 00:07:59,387
At your high school?

96
00:08:00,927 --> 00:08:03,122
[Telephone rings]

97
00:08:09,135 --> 00:08:09,829
Hello.

98
00:08:10,904 --> 00:08:12,496
It's, uh, it's Skip.

99
00:08:14,607 --> 00:08:15,574
What do you want?

100
00:08:15,742 --> 00:08:18,006
I just want...
I wanted... I, I...

101
00:08:18,111 --> 00:08:19,100
<i>You wanted to what?</i>

102
00:08:19,279 --> 00:08:21,076
Call here once every five years
when you're drunk,

103
00:08:21,181 --> 00:08:23,877
or you're stoned off your ass to see
how fabulous we're getting along?

104
00:08:25,285 --> 00:08:26,616
I, uh...

105
00:08:28,822 --> 00:08:29,789
Yeah, I thought so.

106
00:08:29,889 --> 00:08:31,117
[Disconnects phone]

107
00:08:32,125 --> 00:08:34,025
[Shuts phone]

108
00:08:34,194 --> 00:08:35,855
Mom.

109
00:08:35,962 --> 00:08:37,953
Are you okay?

110
00:08:40,700 --> 00:08:43,260
MONA: Your place is the biggest.
CARRIE: It's not a good idea.

111
00:08:43,369 --> 00:08:45,837
Everyone will bring something.
It will be easy.

112
00:08:45,939 --> 00:08:50,501
Besides, I kind of
already invited Vince.

113
00:08:50,610 --> 00:08:52,077
Oh, my God.
You did not!

114
00:08:52,178 --> 00:08:54,146
And he accepted.

115
00:08:54,247 --> 00:08:55,874
- No, he didn't!
- Mm-hmm.

116
00:08:55,982 --> 00:08:57,006
- He did?
- Mm-hmm.

117
00:08:57,183 --> 00:08:58,980
Mona, who else did you invite?

118
00:08:59,152 --> 00:09:00,642
All the losers.

119
00:09:00,820 --> 00:09:02,981
Julie in Reception.

120
00:09:03,156 --> 00:09:04,885
She got new boobs,
and her husband still left her.

121
00:09:04,991 --> 00:09:06,481
Now she's in perpetual heat.

122
00:09:06,593 --> 00:09:08,083
Jimbo in Surgery Prep.

123
00:09:08,261 --> 00:09:09,956
He just relocated from Montana.

124
00:09:10,063 --> 00:09:11,826
That Neanderthal guy
who wears the cowboy boots

125
00:09:11,931 --> 00:09:12,955
with the bad teeth?

126
00:09:13,066 --> 00:09:15,159
You invited him to my house
on Christmas Eve?

127
00:09:15,268 --> 00:09:17,998
He's divorced.
He knows absolutely nobody.

128
00:09:18,171 --> 00:09:21,197
And lastly, Bedpan Bob.

129
00:09:21,374 --> 00:09:22,898
No. I can't.

130
00:09:23,009 --> 00:09:25,705
The house is an absolute wreck.
I'm behind on the payments.

131
00:09:25,812 --> 00:09:27,677
My credit cards are maxed.
I can't.

132
00:09:27,847 --> 00:09:30,782
It will be fun.
It will be cheap.

133
00:09:30,884 --> 00:09:32,943
You got something better to do
on Christmas Eve?

134
00:09:33,119 --> 00:09:35,053
I sure as hell don't.

135
00:09:35,154 --> 00:09:36,178
What about Danny?

136
00:09:36,356 --> 00:09:38,756
He can come.

137
00:09:39,592 --> 00:09:41,822
He'll be fine.

138
00:09:41,928 --> 00:09:44,362
Mona!

139
00:09:47,200 --> 00:09:49,191
[Laughter]

140
00:09:49,302 --> 00:09:50,496
MONA: She wears her scrubs...

141
00:09:50,603 --> 00:09:51,695
VINCE: So, I decided
to start fresh.

142
00:09:51,804 --> 00:09:53,032
...to the beauty parlor.

143
00:09:53,139 --> 00:09:54,197
She's a fashion nightmare.

144
00:09:54,307 --> 00:09:56,366
BOB: You can never
have too much wine.

145
00:09:58,311 --> 00:09:59,573
My grandmother used to do that.

146
00:10:00,446 --> 00:10:02,038
She had no teeth,
and she went...

147
00:10:02,148 --> 00:10:04,548
[Laughter]

148
00:10:04,651 --> 00:10:07,142
BOB: My grandmother,
she had too many teeth.

149
00:10:07,320 --> 00:10:10,118
Yeah, it made a weird
whistling noise when she ate

150
00:10:10,290 --> 00:10:11,951
and when she talked.

151
00:10:12,058 --> 00:10:14,925
And the thing was, not all her teeth
were in her mouth.

152
00:10:15,094 --> 00:10:16,425
Oh, that's so funny.

153
00:10:16,529 --> 00:10:17,427
That is so cute.

154
00:10:17,597 --> 00:10:20,293
Danny, honey, I need you
out here now, please!

155
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:22,425
Bogus, Bob.

156
00:10:22,602 --> 00:10:23,626
[Door closes]

157
00:10:23,736 --> 00:10:25,533
MONA:
Hey!

158
00:10:26,506 --> 00:10:28,804
Hi, sweetie.

159
00:10:30,209 --> 00:10:31,870
Jimbo!

160
00:10:31,978 --> 00:10:34,242
Please, could you not do that
at the table?

161
00:10:34,347 --> 00:10:39,284
So, Carrie, uh,
Mona told me that you were

162
00:10:39,385 --> 00:10:43,446
considering going
to San Francisco on rotation.

163
00:10:43,623 --> 00:10:47,525
Well, I applied,
but I haven't been accepted yet.

164
00:10:47,627 --> 00:10:52,428
Oh. Well, if there's anything I can do
to make sure it doesn't happen...

165
00:10:52,598 --> 00:10:54,088
[Laughter]

166
00:10:55,802 --> 00:10:57,531
Please pass me a roll.

167
00:10:57,637 --> 00:10:58,467
Sure.

168
00:10:59,706 --> 00:11:01,071
Didn't you bring something, Bob?

169
00:11:01,174 --> 00:11:02,698
I brought ham.

170
00:11:02,875 --> 00:11:03,500
Oh!

171
00:11:03,609 --> 00:11:04,541
Hey!

172
00:11:04,711 --> 00:11:05,370
Anybody?

173
00:11:05,545 --> 00:11:08,070
- Bedpan, I...
- [Laughter]

174
00:11:08,247 --> 00:11:09,839
Why do they call you Bedpan?

175
00:11:10,016 --> 00:11:11,142
Danny.

176
00:11:11,317 --> 00:11:13,615
Perhaps it's because
emptying bedpans

177
00:11:13,720 --> 00:11:17,417
for the very ill patients
is among the duties I perform.

178
00:11:17,523 --> 00:11:19,150
Oh, I hope you washed your hands.

179
00:11:19,325 --> 00:11:20,223
- Danny.
- Danny.

180
00:11:20,393 --> 00:11:21,724
You have to go to college for that?

181
00:11:21,894 --> 00:11:23,225
- [Laughter]
- [Knock on door]

182
00:11:23,329 --> 00:11:25,160
I'll get it.

183
00:11:25,331 --> 00:11:25,820
Let me.

184
00:11:25,932 --> 00:11:27,866
No, no, no, no. I'll get it.

185
00:11:29,035 --> 00:11:30,798
Well, are we gonna eat this or what?

186
00:11:33,072 --> 00:11:34,972
Hello. I'm Mona.

187
00:11:36,476 --> 00:11:38,467
Carrie didn't tell me
someone else was coming.

188
00:11:38,644 --> 00:11:40,043
Oh!

189
00:11:40,213 --> 00:11:42,647
Come on in.

190
00:11:43,950 --> 00:11:46,817
[Indistinct conversation]

191
00:11:48,254 --> 00:11:50,882
MONA: Everyone,
we have an extra guest.

192
00:11:50,990 --> 00:11:51,922
This is...

193
00:11:52,025 --> 00:11:53,287
I don't know who you are.

194
00:11:53,393 --> 00:11:54,826
[Laughs tipsily]

195
00:11:54,994 --> 00:11:59,556
That is Skip, my long-lost,
so-called brother.

196
00:12:01,167 --> 00:12:03,431
- VINCE: Brother?
- CARRIE: Mm-hmm.

197
00:12:05,405 --> 00:12:06,929
I hope I'm not interrupting anything.

198
00:12:07,040 --> 00:12:08,302
Are you kidding?

199
00:12:08,408 --> 00:12:11,571
From where I'm sitting,
you're an absolute hero.

200
00:12:12,178 --> 00:12:13,770
Wine?

201
00:12:16,349 --> 00:12:18,340
What do you do?

202
00:12:18,518 --> 00:12:21,078
I produce...

203
00:12:21,988 --> 00:12:23,012
...films.

204
00:12:23,189 --> 00:12:25,680
BOB: Mmm...
Anything we'd know?

205
00:12:27,193 --> 00:12:28,922
[Sniffs]

206
00:12:29,028 --> 00:12:30,086
Hey, Danny.

207
00:12:30,797 --> 00:12:33,027
Danny.

208
00:12:35,201 --> 00:12:37,294
VINCE:
Uh, hey, everybody.

209
00:12:37,403 --> 00:12:39,166
You know what?
Why don't we do this another time?

210
00:12:39,272 --> 00:12:40,967
Yes, that's right.
Everybody out.

211
00:12:41,074 --> 00:12:43,941
- But we didn't eat anything yet.
- Take your food with you, Jimbo.

212
00:12:44,043 --> 00:12:47,774
Come on. <i>Feliz Navidad.</i>
<i>Adiós,</i> everybody.

213
00:12:47,880 --> 00:12:49,848
Good night, you guys.
Thank you.

214
00:12:50,016 --> 00:12:51,381
You don't know
what you're missing.

215
00:12:51,484 --> 00:12:52,712
MONA:
Let's go!

216
00:12:52,819 --> 00:12:53,717
Where's my purse?

217
00:12:53,820 --> 00:12:56,186
Don't worry about it.
I'll help you find it. Let's go.

218
00:12:56,289 --> 00:12:59,315
BOB: Let's do this again
when we have less time.

219
00:13:00,493 --> 00:13:02,085
What the hell
are you doing here?

220
00:13:02,195 --> 00:13:03,992
Excuse me, Carrie, Carrie.

221
00:13:04,097 --> 00:13:05,496
Excuse me, sir.

222
00:13:05,665 --> 00:13:08,031
Just give me one minute, please.

223
00:13:11,270 --> 00:13:13,534
This is a bad idea.

224
00:13:20,113 --> 00:13:21,774
[Door closes]

225
00:13:21,881 --> 00:13:23,849
[Sniffs]

226
00:13:31,257 --> 00:13:33,487
[Door closes]

227
00:13:54,480 --> 00:13:57,108
We don't want you here.

228
00:13:58,351 --> 00:14:00,285
Get out.

229
00:14:01,687 --> 00:14:03,655
Get out!

230
00:14:21,774 --> 00:14:24,038
DANNY:
I hate you!

231
00:14:24,977 --> 00:14:28,469
I hate you!
We don't want you here!

232
00:14:30,249 --> 00:14:32,080
[Grunts]

233
00:14:37,490 --> 00:14:39,185
MONA:
I am so sorry.

234
00:14:43,863 --> 00:14:45,387
I knew it.

235
00:14:45,565 --> 00:14:46,190
No.

236
00:14:46,299 --> 00:14:47,766
I didn't get accepted.

237
00:14:47,934 --> 00:14:49,834
MONA: We regret to inform you,
blah, blah, blah...

238
00:14:51,470 --> 00:14:52,937
...more qualified candidate.

239
00:14:56,542 --> 00:14:57,531
I'll talk to you later.

240
00:15:14,193 --> 00:15:16,218
I'd like to try with Danny somehow.

241
00:15:18,531 --> 00:15:19,828
Why didn't you want to try
15 years ago

242
00:15:19,932 --> 00:15:21,229
when it might have made
a difference?

243
00:15:21,400 --> 00:15:22,526
I know it's late.

244
00:15:22,635 --> 00:15:25,661
It's way too late.
He's 17 years old.

245
00:15:25,838 --> 00:15:30,366
He has no hopes, no self-esteem,
no interest in anything.

246
00:15:30,476 --> 00:15:34,412
Congratulations,
you are a great father.

247
00:15:35,081 --> 00:15:36,070
I need to see him.

248
00:15:36,249 --> 00:15:37,944
[Scoffs]

249
00:15:38,050 --> 00:15:40,883
Well, that's too bad, because
in case you hadn't noticed,

250
00:15:40,987 --> 00:15:43,922
he really didn't want
to see you, did he?

251
00:15:44,023 --> 00:15:47,550
But what the hell. You know what?
Go ahead. It's your funeral.

252
00:15:47,727 --> 00:15:49,285
Oh.

253
00:15:49,395 --> 00:15:51,556
You don't do funerals, do you?

254
00:15:51,664 --> 00:15:53,256
Least of all, your own father's.

255
00:15:54,400 --> 00:15:55,731
I had issues at the time.

256
00:15:55,901 --> 00:15:57,232
You had issues at the time!

257
00:15:57,336 --> 00:15:58,633
He was your father!

258
00:15:58,804 --> 00:16:00,738
He loved you.

259
00:16:00,906 --> 00:16:03,238
He talked for years
about you coming home.

260
00:16:03,342 --> 00:16:04,969
He sat in that damn barn,

261
00:16:05,077 --> 00:16:08,569
and he dropped dead
waiting for you to come home!

262
00:16:08,748 --> 00:16:10,511
And what about Danny?

263
00:16:10,616 --> 00:16:13,983
Waiting for his Daddy,
his Daddy who forgot his birthday,

264
00:16:14,086 --> 00:16:15,110
who forgot Christmas,

265
00:16:15,221 --> 00:16:18,554
who didn't give a damn
about anybody but himself.

266
00:16:19,258 --> 00:16:22,489
Did you think about me
for two seconds?

267
00:16:23,095 --> 00:16:25,791
Hoping that you'd come home
and help me raise your kid

268
00:16:25,898 --> 00:16:27,991
so that maybe one of my marriages
would work out,

269
00:16:28,100 --> 00:16:31,001
I could start a family
of my own?

270
00:16:31,103 --> 00:16:34,834
You know why they left?
They couldn't handle Danny...

271
00:16:34,940 --> 00:16:38,569
Your son.
Not my son, your son.

272
00:16:40,112 --> 00:16:44,640
So, there...
you screwed up three lives.

273
00:16:45,318 --> 00:16:47,377
How are those for issues?

274
00:16:50,990 --> 00:16:52,082
Could you talk to him?

275
00:16:52,258 --> 00:16:55,591
You want to talk to him,
you talk to him yourself.

276
00:16:55,695 --> 00:16:58,687
Do you know what?
You don't have the guts.

277
00:16:58,798 --> 00:17:01,232
You might be some big shot
in Hollywood,

278
00:17:01,334 --> 00:17:04,360
but when it comes to the things
that really matter in this life,

279
00:17:04,470 --> 00:17:05,528
you are nothing.

280
00:17:05,705 --> 00:17:08,230
You're nothing.

281
00:17:16,148 --> 00:17:17,513
MONA:
What do you think he wants?

282
00:17:18,617 --> 00:17:20,448
I don't have any idea.

283
00:17:20,553 --> 00:17:22,453
It's weird.

284
00:17:22,888 --> 00:17:26,187
What you need is
some retail therapy.

285
00:17:26,292 --> 00:17:27,987
Mm-hmm.

286
00:17:28,094 --> 00:17:29,459
What? Money's tight?

287
00:17:29,562 --> 00:17:31,928
Yeah. When isn't it?

288
00:17:32,031 --> 00:17:36,263
Well, that rotation in San Francisco
will do you some good.

289
00:17:36,369 --> 00:17:39,065
That's a lousy thing to say, Mona.

290
00:17:39,171 --> 00:17:40,900
Is it?

291
00:17:44,110 --> 00:17:46,203
Congratulations.

292
00:17:46,312 --> 00:17:48,280
How did you do this?

293
00:17:48,381 --> 00:17:49,405
Oh!

294
00:17:49,515 --> 00:17:53,212
A certain doctor that we know
made a phone call.

295
00:17:53,986 --> 00:17:54,816
What about Danny?

296
00:17:54,920 --> 00:17:57,354
Danny is old enough
to take care of himself.

297
00:17:57,456 --> 00:17:59,390
Or he should be.

298
00:18:12,071 --> 00:18:16,303
[Police dispatch chatter]

299
00:18:24,784 --> 00:18:26,649
Danny!

300
00:18:29,355 --> 00:18:30,947
[Activates answering machine]

301
00:18:31,056 --> 00:18:31,784
[Beep]

302
00:18:31,891 --> 00:18:34,451
DANNY:
<i>Mom, it's me.</i>

303
00:18:34,560 --> 00:18:36,619
<i>I'm in jail.</i>

304
00:18:37,496 --> 00:18:39,293
<i>Please come get me.</i>

305
00:18:39,398 --> 00:18:41,389
<i>Please.</i>

306
00:18:41,500 --> 00:18:43,434
[Beep]

307
00:18:43,769 --> 00:18:45,930
[Whispering]:
Shut up!

308
00:18:46,906 --> 00:18:49,101
For bail? A bondsman
will want 10º% up front.

309
00:18:49,308 --> 00:18:50,866
If I put the house up,
I could lose it.

310
00:18:50,976 --> 00:18:52,534
You don't have the money
to get him out.

311
00:18:52,645 --> 00:18:54,203
What are you saying?
I shouldn't go see him?

312
00:18:54,313 --> 00:18:57,282
No, I'm saying that you don't have
the money to get him out,

313
00:18:57,450 --> 00:18:59,543
but his daddy does.

314
00:18:59,652 --> 00:19:00,448
Skip?

315
00:19:00,619 --> 00:19:04,146
No. No, absolutely not.
I can't go to him for help.

316
00:19:04,323 --> 00:19:05,483
- He wants to see him.
- No.

317
00:19:05,591 --> 00:19:06,683
Make the deal with him.

318
00:19:06,792 --> 00:19:09,352
He gets him out, and he stays
with Danny while you're away.

319
00:19:09,995 --> 00:19:10,893
Oh, right, yeah...

320
00:19:10,996 --> 00:19:12,964
I'm gonna leave those two alone
after what happened

321
00:19:13,065 --> 00:19:14,157
last time they saw each other?

322
00:19:14,266 --> 00:19:16,393
You think you can fix it?
Let them work it out.

323
00:19:17,269 --> 00:19:19,829
There might be something
that you just can't do for Danny.

324
00:19:19,939 --> 00:19:22,430
Let them work it out.

325
00:19:22,942 --> 00:19:26,139
God knows you could use
the change of scenery.

326
00:19:45,498 --> 00:19:46,863
Mom.

327
00:19:46,966 --> 00:19:47,864
Are you okay?

328
00:19:48,767 --> 00:19:50,234
I guess so.

329
00:19:50,336 --> 00:19:52,463
Except for being in here.

330
00:19:52,571 --> 00:19:53,833
Mom, the cops just came and...

331
00:19:54,006 --> 00:19:58,909
Danny, honey.
Your bail is $50,000.

332
00:20:00,546 --> 00:20:03,447
So, if you want to get out of here,
you have to do something for me.

333
00:20:04,950 --> 00:20:06,110
Anything.

334
00:20:06,218 --> 00:20:09,312
Okay. Just remember you said that.

335
00:20:10,089 --> 00:20:13,889
Now, remember I told you I applied
for that San Francisco rotation?

336
00:20:13,993 --> 00:20:14,823
I got it.

337
00:20:14,927 --> 00:20:17,020
So, I'm going to be going
out of town, and...

338
00:20:17,129 --> 00:20:17,458
Mom.

339
00:20:17,630 --> 00:20:19,063
Honey, we need the money.

340
00:20:19,164 --> 00:20:22,099
I'm behind on the bills.

341
00:20:24,837 --> 00:20:29,365
So, I need you to stay at the house

342
00:20:29,475 --> 00:20:31,500
and I need you to promise me

343
00:20:31,610 --> 00:20:36,047
that you'll get along
with whoever is there with you, okay?

344
00:20:36,882 --> 00:20:37,974
Is it Mona?

345
00:20:38,083 --> 00:20:40,449
No, it's not Mona.

346
00:20:40,553 --> 00:20:42,521
Is it the bedpan guy?
Please mom, not the...

347
00:20:42,621 --> 00:20:45,283
No, it's not the bedpan guy.

348
00:20:48,260 --> 00:20:50,057
Now, look, just promise me this,

349
00:20:50,162 --> 00:20:53,757
and you'll be out of here
tomorrow morning, okay?

350
00:20:54,967 --> 00:20:57,458
Danny, I need to hear the words.

351
00:20:57,570 --> 00:20:58,434
I promise.

352
00:20:59,438 --> 00:21:01,429
I promise.

353
00:21:02,241 --> 00:21:04,004
Okay.

354
00:21:05,811 --> 00:21:07,608
I love you, honey.

355
00:21:07,713 --> 00:21:10,147
It's gonna be okay.

356
00:21:15,955 --> 00:21:17,946
Wait, Mom!

357
00:21:18,057 --> 00:21:19,786
Mom, don't leave!

358
00:21:19,892 --> 00:21:21,655
Mom!

359
00:21:21,760 --> 00:21:23,125
Mom!

360
00:21:37,876 --> 00:21:41,004
The bank doesn't open until 9:30.

361
00:21:43,015 --> 00:21:44,778
<i>Elliot, it's Skip.</i>

362
00:21:45,351 --> 00:21:47,182
No, we need to talk, Elliot.

363
00:21:47,286 --> 00:21:48,776
Yeah, tonight.

364
00:21:48,887 --> 00:21:50,514
ELLIOT:
God, I don't know what to say, Skip.

365
00:21:52,524 --> 00:21:55,391
There's... There's gotta be
another way.

366
00:21:55,494 --> 00:21:57,291
There's not.

367
00:21:57,763 --> 00:21:58,695
What?

368
00:21:59,765 --> 00:22:01,790
No, I mean,

369
00:22:01,900 --> 00:22:04,061
it's just that you
can't use your son like that.

370
00:22:04,236 --> 00:22:06,170
I'm gonna talk to him,
see if he's okay with it.

371
00:22:07,740 --> 00:22:10,504
Let me understand
something here, Skip.

372
00:22:10,609 --> 00:22:14,136
You shoot heroin
into your veins for kicks, right?

373
00:22:14,246 --> 00:22:16,544
Years later, it destroys your liver.

374
00:22:16,649 --> 00:22:19,140
Now you want me to keep
this poor kid out of jail

375
00:22:19,251 --> 00:22:20,980
so you can con him
out of a piece of his?

376
00:22:21,153 --> 00:22:23,246
I told you, there's no time!

377
00:22:23,422 --> 00:22:24,753
It's just a little surgery.

378
00:22:24,857 --> 00:22:26,324
It's major surgery.

379
00:22:26,425 --> 00:22:27,858
Things can happen.

380
00:22:28,027 --> 00:22:30,154
This is my life
we're talking about, Elliot.

381
00:22:30,329 --> 00:22:31,489
You are way over the line here.

382
00:22:31,664 --> 00:22:33,188
I don't think I'm breaking any laws.

383
00:22:33,365 --> 00:22:36,823
The boy is not an organ bank.
He's a human being.

384
00:22:37,002 --> 00:22:37,832
So am I.

385
00:22:37,936 --> 00:22:40,632
Oh, Skip. I know how you work.

386
00:22:40,739 --> 00:22:44,300
The manipulation,
playing on people's emotions,

387
00:22:44,410 --> 00:22:45,638
getting what <i>you</i> want.

388
00:22:45,744 --> 00:22:47,712
The deals, the women.

389
00:22:47,880 --> 00:22:50,178
And for 15 years
I've been right there with you.

390
00:22:52,885 --> 00:22:54,011
He's my only chance.

391
00:22:54,186 --> 00:22:56,711
Then face the reality, Skip.
Face it!

392
00:22:58,957 --> 00:23:01,926
Come to think of it,
you are breaking a law.

393
00:23:02,027 --> 00:23:03,289
A higher law.

394
00:23:06,832 --> 00:23:08,459
You just keep Danny out of jail.

395
00:23:40,365 --> 00:23:44,324
Hey, Skip. Come here.
I want to show you something.

396
00:23:57,149 --> 00:23:59,743
Wait a second, we got to talk.

397
00:23:59,852 --> 00:24:01,615
Danny!

398
00:24:04,957 --> 00:24:07,517
[Skip whistles]

399
00:24:42,161 --> 00:24:45,096
Be a man.
Tell the truth.

400
00:24:46,165 --> 00:24:48,725
Take responsibility.

401
00:24:49,601 --> 00:24:51,466
It's all I want from you.

402
00:24:57,075 --> 00:25:00,010
Get yourself a beer,
and give me a hand.

403
00:25:00,112 --> 00:25:02,910
No, I'm too busy.

404
00:25:03,015 --> 00:25:07,543
Okay, it'll be here waiting for you.

405
00:25:25,838 --> 00:25:26,862
What do you want?

406
00:25:27,973 --> 00:25:28,803
Nothing.

407
00:25:29,575 --> 00:25:31,042
That's a lie.
Why are you still here?

408
00:25:32,010 --> 00:25:32,999
Because I want to be.

409
00:25:34,613 --> 00:25:35,705
Another lie.

410
00:25:52,531 --> 00:25:56,865
We got, uh, vegetarian, pepperoni...

411
00:25:57,936 --> 00:25:59,801
Good stuff.

412
00:26:07,779 --> 00:26:09,212
[Door slams]

413
00:26:16,788 --> 00:26:18,483
Good morning.

414
00:26:45,550 --> 00:26:47,040
[Cabinet door slams]

415
00:26:47,152 --> 00:26:51,782
[Dishes clatter]

416
00:26:51,890 --> 00:26:52,982
[Objects crashing]

417
00:26:53,091 --> 00:26:55,582
Careful.

418
00:27:28,927 --> 00:27:31,327
[Telephone rings]

419
00:27:42,941 --> 00:27:44,169
Hello.

420
00:27:44,276 --> 00:27:45,470
Hey.

421
00:27:45,577 --> 00:27:46,805
No, everything is...

422
00:27:46,912 --> 00:27:49,437
[Loud crash]

423
00:27:53,952 --> 00:27:54,976
...fine.

424
00:28:14,706 --> 00:28:16,503
Don't you ever steal from me!

425
00:28:16,675 --> 00:28:18,267
If you need money,
you just ask me.

426
00:28:19,144 --> 00:28:21,908
Now give me those pills back,
I need them.

427
00:28:22,681 --> 00:28:24,148
Don't you walk away from me!

428
00:28:24,249 --> 00:28:26,217
Look who's talking!

429
00:29:48,834 --> 00:29:50,165
<i>Hello.</i>

430
00:29:50,335 --> 00:29:54,032
Yeah, I need to get
a prescription refilled.

431
00:29:56,775 --> 00:29:59,107
You know what?
This cell reception is pretty...

432
00:29:59,211 --> 00:30:00,439
It's really bad in this area.

433
00:30:00,545 --> 00:30:02,911
When he gets in, can you have him
call me at this number?

434
00:30:06,585 --> 00:30:08,314
You're taking
more than prescribed, aren't you?

435
00:30:09,454 --> 00:30:10,216
No.

436
00:30:14,126 --> 00:30:15,218
We've got to get things going.

437
00:30:16,595 --> 00:30:18,654
I need more time.

438
00:32:53,718 --> 00:32:56,653
You got yourself a very old bike here.

439
00:32:57,989 --> 00:32:59,923
It's a 16 Indian,
or what's left of it.

440
00:33:00,025 --> 00:33:02,323
SHELBY:
It's a 17.

441
00:33:04,596 --> 00:33:05,528
It's a 17.

442
00:33:06,765 --> 00:33:09,928
I don't bring her with me
just because she's my daughter.

443
00:33:10,035 --> 00:33:11,502
Can it be restored?

444
00:33:11,603 --> 00:33:15,596
Yeah, anything can be restored.
Just time and effort.

445
00:33:15,774 --> 00:33:18,174
You're missing a lot of pieces.
Some we can pick up.

446
00:33:18,276 --> 00:33:21,507
You'll need specs, a catalogue,
chrome work.

447
00:33:21,613 --> 00:33:22,637
Can we assemble it here?

448
00:33:23,114 --> 00:33:25,981
No. No, it's got to be done at a shop.

449
00:33:26,084 --> 00:33:28,177
But we've got lots of tools here.

450
00:33:28,286 --> 00:33:30,277
This isn't like building
a model airplane.

451
00:33:30,388 --> 00:33:32,015
You need someone
who knows what they're doing.

452
00:33:33,358 --> 00:33:35,553
You're right.
You're hired.

453
00:33:39,064 --> 00:33:40,053
I don't think that...

454
00:33:40,231 --> 00:33:41,129
Wait a minute.

455
00:33:42,934 --> 00:33:45,562
What kind of money
are we talking about here?

456
00:34:07,759 --> 00:34:08,589
Hi.

457
00:34:09,994 --> 00:34:12,292
I see you two have met.

458
00:34:16,334 --> 00:34:18,302
Let's get started.

459
00:34:19,104 --> 00:34:22,437
Danny, you're welcome
to join us, if you'd like.

460
00:34:27,379 --> 00:34:29,609
That's a nice bike.

461
00:34:29,714 --> 00:34:31,682
Thanks.

462
00:34:38,723 --> 00:34:41,214
It's a 17, just like I said.

463
00:34:41,326 --> 00:34:46,286
Everything needs to be cleaned
and rechromed and painted.

464
00:34:47,065 --> 00:34:50,330
It's not going to be easy
finding what's missing.

465
00:34:50,435 --> 00:34:52,369
The hard part's always the prep work.

466
00:34:52,470 --> 00:34:54,461
And, of course,
putting it all together.

467
00:34:54,672 --> 00:34:56,071
[Engine revs]

468
00:35:10,422 --> 00:35:13,357
Danny's a bit of a show off
this morning.

469
00:35:16,394 --> 00:35:19,192
So, I'll come back tomorrow
and catalogue what's missing?

470
00:35:19,297 --> 00:35:22,095
No, not tomorrow, I've got a...
I've got a commitment.

471
00:35:22,267 --> 00:35:24,633
But in a couple of days?

472
00:35:24,736 --> 00:35:26,397
Sure.

473
00:35:40,585 --> 00:35:43,076
[Knocking on door]

474
00:35:43,254 --> 00:35:45,415
Court tomorrow.

475
00:36:04,509 --> 00:36:07,069
[Whispering] Say whatever it is
you need to say.

476
00:36:07,178 --> 00:36:08,167
Fix your tie.

477
00:36:10,515 --> 00:36:14,576
Your Honor, we do not deny
the charges against my client.

478
00:36:14,686 --> 00:36:18,782
We would, however, suggest
there are mitigating factors.

479
00:36:18,890 --> 00:36:20,687
It is a first offense.

480
00:36:20,792 --> 00:36:22,521
The boy is a minor.

481
00:36:22,627 --> 00:36:23,855
And he has not had the benefit

482
00:36:24,028 --> 00:36:26,053
of joint parental care
and supervision.

483
00:36:26,164 --> 00:36:27,324
Has the mother been absent?

484
00:36:28,500 --> 00:36:31,628
The boy's mother was killed
in a car accident when he was three.

485
00:36:31,736 --> 00:36:33,727
His aunt raised him.

486
00:36:33,838 --> 00:36:34,805
And who are you?

487
00:36:34,906 --> 00:36:35,668
I'm the boy's...

488
00:36:35,773 --> 00:36:36,967
His father.

489
00:36:37,141 --> 00:36:38,267
As such.

490
00:36:39,043 --> 00:36:40,476
I'm sorry, I don't quite understand.

491
00:36:40,578 --> 00:36:43,206
Mr. Gaines has been totally absent
from his son's life

492
00:36:43,314 --> 00:36:46,750
and is therefore totally responsible
for his son's behavior.

493
00:36:46,851 --> 00:36:47,818
Explain.

494
00:36:47,919 --> 00:36:49,614
Extreme negligence.

495
00:36:49,787 --> 00:36:52,483
17 years ago,
Mr. Gaines had a son,

496
00:36:52,590 --> 00:36:55,388
Danny, the defendant.

497
00:36:55,493 --> 00:36:59,293
Did Mr. Gaines remain with him
to teach him right from wrong,

498
00:36:59,397 --> 00:37:01,228
to instill in him the proper values,

499
00:37:01,332 --> 00:37:05,962
to guide him into responsible
adulthood like a father should?

500
00:37:06,070 --> 00:37:07,799
No.

501
00:37:08,139 --> 00:37:11,870
Mr. Gaines abandoned his son's care
to his sister

502
00:37:11,976 --> 00:37:14,240
who tried to be both
mother and father to him.

503
00:37:14,412 --> 00:37:16,403
But as you would observe,
Your Honor,

504
00:37:16,514 --> 00:37:21,918
Danny has, in fact, suffered
from Mr. Gaines' abject disregard

505
00:37:22,020 --> 00:37:23,988
for his own son's welfare.

506
00:37:24,088 --> 00:37:27,319
Mr. Gaines is a callous
and cruel individual, Your Honor.

507
00:37:27,425 --> 00:37:30,588
And I would hope that you would
take these facts into consideration

508
00:37:30,762 --> 00:37:32,923
to prevent a similar outcome
for Danny.

509
00:37:33,031 --> 00:37:35,056
Do you have other children,
Mr. Gaines?

510
00:37:36,100 --> 00:37:37,362
No, not that I know of.

511
00:37:39,837 --> 00:37:41,702
Uh, I mean, no.

512
00:37:41,806 --> 00:37:43,330
No, I do not, Your Honor.

513
00:37:43,441 --> 00:37:45,341
How lucky for them.

514
00:37:48,112 --> 00:37:52,708
You, young man, have a lot to learn
about respect for the rule of law.

515
00:37:52,884 --> 00:37:55,148
I can decide that you are an adult
and try you as one.

516
00:37:55,253 --> 00:37:57,949
Your Honor, I would like to take
full responsibility.

517
00:37:58,056 --> 00:37:59,421
Really? Since when?

518
00:37:59,591 --> 00:38:02,151
My son, uh, doesn't deserve
to go to jail,

519
00:38:02,260 --> 00:38:04,023
and I'll take care
of all the financial, uh...

520
00:38:04,128 --> 00:38:07,222
No, he doesn't. And yes, you will pay
for the financial damage.

521
00:38:08,232 --> 00:38:09,563
But how do you plan on paying

